Household Survey Analysis

Preliminary Results

Published

May 15, 2025

This document presents an initial analysis of the household survey responses from invited residents living within 0.1 mile (0.16 km) of Lafayette Park in Norfolk and Paradise Creek Nature Park in Portsmouth.

The survey itself was constructed using Qualtrics and participants were recruited using mailed postcards, email, and SMS text messaging. The household survey response rate was lower than expected, despite compensation in the form of a $35 gift card as a financial incentive and we received 93 responses from 486 invitations for a response rate of 19.1% percent.

In terms of age distribution, there were far more respondents from Portsmouth in the 60+ years category than from Norfolkâthe two distributions are otherwise similar. There appears to have been more parity in gender identity for Portsmouth respondents.

The responses to the How long have you lived in your current home? question skew towards longer-term residents in Norfolk. The majority of respondents (41%) are renters while in Norfolk that number is 33% and in Portsmouth 53% are renters.

Marital status is similarly distributed between Norfolk and Portsmouth respondents, but far more Portsmouth respondents have other dependents (i.e., not children) living in the household.

Educational attainment (i.e., respondents with a Bachelorâs degree or higher) is higher in Norfolk and this difference is statistically significant (kw = 7.26, p = 0.007). Reported incomes were higher in Norfolk while more Portsmouth respondents indicated they were âFinding it very difficult on present incomeâ.

There is a statistically significant difference in access to a garden with this being more likely among Norfolk respondents (kw = 5.01, p = 0.025).

Note the higher percentage of respondents with a health condition or disability in Portsmouth.

Recode Data from Qualtrics Format

There are several sets of questions designed to capture dimensions of mental and physical well-being as well as social cohesion and neighborhood perceptions. The section below outlines how these question responses were coded to support analysis.

Relationships with Others

These responses comprise the UCLA-3 loneliness scale1 where a lower number represents less loneliness and are coded 1 = Hardly Ever, 2 = Some of the Time, 3 = Often:

  • How often do you feel that you lack companionship? â Q61_1
  • How often do you feel left out? â Q61_2
  • How often do you feel isolated from others? â Q61_3

Social Cohesion and Belonging

For the question below, a higher number represents greater belonging2 and are coded 1 = Not at all strongly, 2 = Not very strongly, 3 = Donât know (neutral), 4 = Fairly strongly, 5 = Very strongly:

  • How strongly do you feel you belong to your neighborhood or local area? â Q62

Subjective Mental Wellbeing

For this measure3, a higher number represents higher mental well-being. These responses are coded 1 = None of the time, 2 = Rarely, 3 = Some of the time, 4 = Often, 5 = All of the time:

  • Iâve been feeling optimistic about the future (over the past two weeks). â Q63_1
  • Iâve been feeling useful (over the past two weeks). â Q63_2
  • Iâve been feeling relaxed (over the past two weeks). â Q63_3
  • Iâve been dealing with problems (over the past two weeks). â Q63_4
  • Iâve been thinking clearly (over the past two weeks). â Q63_5
  • Iâve been feeling close to other people (over the past two weeks). â Q63_6
  • Iâve been able to make up my own mind about things (over the past two weeks). â Q63_7

Perceived Stress

For this measure4 a lower number represents lower stress. These responses are coded 1 = Never, 2 = Almost never, 3 = Sometimes, 4 = Fairly often, 5 = Very often:

  • Felt that you were unable to control the important things in life? (in the last month). â Q64_1
  • Doubted your ability to handle your personal problems? (in the last month). â Q64_2
  • Felt that things were just not going your way? (in the last month). â Q64_3
  • Felt difficulties were piling up so high that you could not overcome them? (in the last month). â Q64_4

General Health

In general would you say that, for a person of your age,your health isâ¦ 1 = Very poor, 2 = Poor, 3 = Neither poor nor good, 4 = Good, 5 = Very good. â Q65

Physical Activity

Brisk physical activity (moderate to intense levels of activity), means it leaves you slightly out of breath and raises your heart rate slightly. Types of brisk physical activity can include walking, cycling, climbing stairs,gardening, energetic housework, etc.

  • How much moderate to intense (or brisk) physical activity do you do on average per week? 1 = None, 2 = Less than 30 minutes, 3 = 30 mins to 1 hour, 4 = 1 hour to 1 Â½ hour, 5 = More than 1 Â½ hours. â Q66
  • During the last 7 days, on how many days did you walk for at least 10 minutes at a time? â Q67
  • How much time (in minutes) did you usually spend walking on one of those days?? â Q68

Perception of Local Neighborhood

These questions capture a respondentâs perceptions of and satisfaction with the neighborhood. A higher value represents higher satisfaction with the local neighborhood.

  • Would you advise a friend or relative to live in this neighborhood? 1 = Definitely not, 2 = Probably not, 3 = Might or might not, 4 = Probably yes, 5 = Definitely yes. â Q69
  • How satisfied are you with the quality of the physical environment in your local neighborhood? 1 = Extremely dissatisfied, 2 = Somewhat dissatisfied, 3 = Neither satisfied nor dissatisfied, 4 = Somewhat satisfied, 5 = Extremely satisfied. â Q70
  • Would you say most people in your neighborhood can be trusted? 1 = Definitely not, 2 = Probably not, 3 = Donât know (neutral), 4 = Probably yes, 5 = Definitely yes. â Q71


Survey Findings

In addition to selected descriptive statistics, we used non-parametric Kruskal-Wallis tests to explore potential differences in outcomes of interest. Note that the null hypothesis for the Kruskal-Wallis test is that the median values of the variable of interest are the same across the groups being comparedâthis test is useful when the data are not normally distributed or when they are ordinal (e.g., Likert scales).

Respondents from Norfolk trust their neighbors at a higher rate (mean = 3.21, sd = 0.91) than in in Portsmouth (mean = 2.66, sd = 0.94). Similarly, respondents in Norfolk are more likely to advise a friend to live in the neighborhood (mean = 3.93, sd = 0.87) and the difference with Portsmouth was significant at the 0.05 alpha level (kw = 6.49, p = 0.011).
